-- Course 1: Fundamentals of Disaster Preparedness (General)
(1,'Understanding Disaster Risk in India','India is one of the world most disaster-prone countries, affected by 26 of 35 major disaster types recognized by the United Nations. Every year, an average of 50 million people are affected by natural disasters in India. The country faces floods (affecting 33 million annually), cyclones (coastline of 7,516 km), earthquakes (57% of land in seismic zones III-V), droughts, heatwaves, landslides, and tsunamis. The National Disaster Management Authority (NDMA) was established under the Disaster Management Act 2005 following the catastrophic 2004 Indian Ocean Tsunami and 2001 Bhuj earthquake. Understanding your local hazard profile is the first step to preparedness. Check ndma.gov.in for your district hazard map.',1,20,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(1,'The Disaster Management Cycle','Disaster management follows a four-phase cycle that every citizen should understand: (1) Mitigation — reducing risk before disaster strikes through building codes, early warning systems, land-use planning, and community awareness. (2) Preparedness — planning, training, stockpiling supplies, and conducting drills before disasters occur. (3) Response — immediate actions during and just after disaster: evacuation, search and rescue, first aid, and relief distribution. (4) Recovery — rebuilding communities, restoring livelihoods, and improving resilience after disaster. India NDMA coordinates all four phases through State Disaster Management Authorities (SDMAs) and District Disaster Management Authorities (DDMAs) at local level.',2,20,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(1,'Building Your Family Disaster Plan','Every Indian household needs a Family Disaster Plan: (1) Identify hazards specific to your area — flood zone, seismic zone, cyclone belt, or industrial area. (2) Map two evacuation routes from your home to higher ground or designated shelter. (3) Choose a family meeting point outside your home and one outside your neighbourhood if separated. (4) Designate an out-of-city contact person for family members to check in with — long-distance calls often work when local lines are jammed. (5) Make a list of emergency numbers: 112 (unified emergency), 108 (ambulance), 1078 (NDMA), local district control room. (6) Practice the plan with all family members including children twice a year.',3,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(1,'The 72-Hour Emergency Kit — India Standard','After any major disaster, government help typically takes 24-72 hours to reach you. Your emergency kit must sustain your family for this period. NDMA recommended kit includes: Water — 4 litres per person per day minimum. Food — ready-to-eat non-perishable items like khakhra, chivda, energy bars, dry fruits. Medicines — prescription medications for 7 days plus basic first aid supplies. Documents — Aadhaar, insurance papers, land records in waterproof bag. Tools — torch with batteries, battery radio for AIR updates, emergency whistle, multi-tool. Communication — fully charged power bank, emergency contact list on paper. Store kit in a grab-and-go bag near your main exit door. Check and refresh every 6 months.',4,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),

-- Course 2: Emergency First Aid & CPR (Medical)
(2,'CPR — Hands-Only Basic Life Support','Cardiac arrest kills within 4-6 minutes without intervention. In India, fewer than 1% of out-of-hospital cardiac arrests survive due to low bystander CPR rates. Hands-only CPR technique: (1) Confirm scene is safe. (2) Tap shoulders and shout — are you okay? (3) Call 108 immediately or ask someone specific to call. (4) Tilt head back, lift chin — check for breathing for no more than 10 seconds. (5) Place heel of hand on centre of chest — lower half of sternum only. (6) Press hard and fast at least 5 cm deep at 100-120 compressions per minute — tempo of Stayin Alive by Bee Gees. (7) Allow full chest recoil — do not lean between compressions. Continue until 108 ambulance arrives.',1,30,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(2,'Bleeding Control and Wound Management','Uncontrolled bleeding is the leading cause of preventable death in trauma. Technique: Apply firm direct pressure with a clean cloth. Do not remove cloth if soaked — add more on top and press harder. For limb bleeding not controlled by pressure within 10 minutes, apply tourniquet 5-7 cm above the wound. Improvised tourniquet: folded cloth at least 5 cm wide tied tightly and twisted with a stick until bleeding stops. Write time of application on patient. Note: never use wire, rope, or thin cord. Wound cleaning: Irrigate with clean water for 5 minutes — not hydrogen peroxide which damages tissue. Cover with clean dressing. Watch for infection signs after 24-48 hours: increasing redness, warmth, swelling, discharge.',2,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(2,'Fractures, Burns, and Spinal Injuries','Fracture management: Immobilize joint above and below fracture using rigid splint — wooden plank, rolled newspaper, or umbrella — padded with cloth. Do not attempt to realign bone. Open fractures with bone visible: cover with clean dressing only. Burns: Cool with running water for minimum 20 minutes — not ice, not butter, not toothpaste. Cover with clean non-fluffy material. Do not burst blisters. Spinal injury: If patient has fallen from height or had significant head or neck impact, assume spinal injury. Do not bend, twist, or move neck. Use log-roll technique with minimum 3 people to move patient onto flat surface. Helmet removal only if patient cannot breathe — requires two-person technique.',3,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(2,'Snakebite, Heatstroke, and Drowning','Snakebite kills 50,000 Indians annually — highest in world. Response: Immobilize bitten limb at or below heart level. Remove all jewellery from bitten limb immediately. Do NOT cut the wound, suck the venom, apply tourniquet, or apply any traditional remedies. Transport urgently to nearest government hospital — only WHO-approved polyvalent anti-venom works. Heatstroke — core temperature above 40 degrees, confusion, hot dry skin: Cool immediately with water, fan, and ice packs to neck, armpits, and groin. Call 108. Drowning: Remove from water using rope or clothing — do not enter fast-moving water without training. Begin CPR immediately if not breathing normally. All drowning victims need hospital evaluation regardless of initial appearance.',4,30,1,NOW(),NOW()),

-- Course 11: Flood Safety & Survival
(11,'Understanding Floods and Early Warning India','India experiences three types of floods: riverine floods from monsoon overflow of major rivers, flash floods from sudden intense rainfall in hilly terrain, and coastal flooding from cyclone storm surges. The Brahmaputra, Ganga, Mahanadi, Godavari, Krishna, and Cauvery river systems cause most riverine flooding. Over 40 million hectares of Indian land is flood-prone. The Central Water Commission monitors over 5,000 river gauging stations and issues three-tier flood warnings: Watch (below danger level), Alert (approaching danger level), and Danger (above danger level). Download the Sachet NDMA app and register your location to receive flood warnings. Also monitor indiawris.gov.in for real-time river level data in your district.',1,20,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(11,'Flood Preparedness at Home and Community','Before monsoon season every year: (1) Know if your home is in a flood-prone zone — check district flood control map. (2) Store drinking water in elevated locations. (3) Waterproof your important documents — Aadhaar, land records, insurance — in sealed ziplock bags placed in a waterproof container. (4) Keep a 72-hour emergency kit on upper floor. (5) Know two evacuation routes to higher ground and the location of your nearest government flood shelter. (6) Trim trees near your home. (7) Keep emergency numbers saved: 1078 NDMA, 112 police, 108 ambulance, and your district flood control room number. Community action: Participate in your local ward flood preparedness meeting organized by your municipality before June 1 every year.',2,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(11,'During and After Flood — Safe Actions','During flood warning: Move immediately to upper floors or higher ground — do not delay waiting to see if it floods. Turn off electricity at main breaker before water enters your home. Never touch electrical equipment while standing in water. Do not walk or drive through floodwater — 15 cm of fast-moving water knocks adults down and 30 cm can sweep away a vehicle. Avoid all floodwater contact — it contains sewage, industrial chemicals, and displaced venomous snakes. If trapped on roof: signal with bright cloth or torch and wait for rescue. Call 112. After flood: Do not return until authorities declare safe. Boil all water. Watch for leptospirosis symptoms — fever, muscle pain, red eyes — appearing 2-14 days after flood exposure. Contact district administration for SDRF compensation claim.',3,20,1,NOW(),NOW()),

-- Course 12: Earthquake Response Training
(12,'Seismic Zones and Building Safety in India','India is divided into four seismic zones by the Bureau of Indian Standards per IS 1893:2016. Zone II — low damage risk: parts of South India, Rajasthan. Zone III — moderate: Most of Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh, parts of UP. Zone IV — high: Delhi, J&K, Himachal Pradesh, UP, Bihar. Zone V — very high: Entire Northeast India, Uttarakhand, Kashmir, parts of Gujarat (Kutch), and Andaman & Nicobar Islands. Over 60% of India land area is in Zone III or above. Buildings constructed before 1985 may not meet any seismic code requirements. The 2001 Bhuj earthquake killed 20,085 — most in non-engineered masonry buildings. Check your seismic zone at bhukosh.gsi.gov.in and consult a structural engineer if your building shows diagonal cracks at window corners.',1,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(12,'Drop Cover Hold — Earthquake Response','During ground shaking — the only three things that matter: DROP to hands and knees immediately. This protects you from being thrown down and keeps you mobile. COVER your head and neck under a sturdy table or desk. If no table is available, cover head and neck with both arms and get against an interior wall away from windows. HOLD ON to your shelter until shaking completely stops — earthquakes can last from seconds to over 2 minutes. Critical myths to unlearn: Do NOT run outside — most earthquake injuries occur when people run through falling debris. Do NOT stand in doorways — this dangerous myth has caused many deaths. Do NOT use elevators. If in bed, stay there and cover head with pillow.',2,20,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(12,'Post-Earthquake Safety and Aftershocks','After shaking stops: Check yourself for injuries before moving. Expect aftershocks — they can occur for days to months and may be strong enough to collapse already-weakened buildings. Inspect for hazards before moving through building: Gas leak — smell or hissing sound means open windows, leave immediately, do not use any switches, call gas emergency from outside. Electrical hazard — damaged wiring, sparks, smell of burning. Structural damage — diagonal cracks at window corners, separation of walls from ceiling or floor, visible steel reinforcing bars, leaning walls. Do not re-enter any building with these signs. Contact municipality for structural safety assessment. Register with your district DDMA at 1800-180-4188.',3,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),

-- Course 13: Cyclone Preparedness - Bay of Bengal
(13,'Bay of Bengal Cyclone Formation and Warnings','The Bay of Bengal is one of the most cyclone-active ocean basins in the world, generating over 7% of global tropical cyclones annually. Cyclone season: April to June and October to December. States most vulnerable: Odisha, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, West Bengal, and Puducherry. IMD four-stage warning system: Pre-Cyclone Watch issued 96 hours before landfall, Cyclone Alert 48 hours before, Cyclone Warning 24 hours before, Post-Landfall Outlook after landfall. IMD color-coded warnings: Green — no threat, Yellow — be updated, Orange — be prepared to act, Red — take action immediately. Track cyclones in real time at mausam.imd.gov.in. Subscribe to IMD alerts via the Mausam app. Storm surge — the wall of seawater pushed ashore by cyclone winds — is the deadliest component, not wind.',1,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(13,'Cyclone Safety Actions Before During and After','Before cyclone: Reinforce roof with additional fasteners. Board windows with plywood or shutters. Trim all trees near the house. Bring inside gas cylinders, two-wheelers, and all loose objects. Fill all containers with water — supply will be cut. Charge all devices and power banks. Know your nearest cyclone shelter. During cyclone: Stay in the innermost room on lowest floor if not flood-prone. Keep away from all windows. If roof begins to lift, lie flat under strongest table available. Do NOT go outside during the eye — the second wall follows. After cyclone: Treat every downed power line as live — do not approach. Do not enter damaged buildings. Boil all water. Report trapped persons to SDRF helpline. Cyclone Fani 2019 key achievement: Odisha evacuated 1.2 million people in 48 hours achieving near-zero deaths through years of community preparedness.',2,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),

-- Course 16: Heatwave Survival Guide
(16,'Heatwave Science and India Vulnerability','A heatwave in India is officially declared when the maximum temperature exceeds 40 degrees Celsius in plains (45 degrees in desert areas) or is 4.5 degrees above the normal maximum for that date. India has seen a 300% increase in heatwave frequency over the past 50 years due to climate change. The 2015 Andhra Pradesh and Telangana heatwave was India deadliest heat event, killing 2,500 in two weeks. Most vulnerable populations: outdoor labourers including construction workers, farmers, and daily wage workers; elderly persons above 65; children under 5; persons with heart disease, diabetes, or respiratory conditions. Heat Index — how hot it actually feels — combines temperature and humidity. At 38 degrees Celsius with 80% relative humidity, the effective temperature on the human body is 55 degrees.',1,20,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(16,'Heat Illness Recognition and Emergency Response','Heat cramps: muscle spasms during exercise in heat — move to cool place, drink ORS, rest. Heat exhaustion: heavy sweating, weakness, cold pale clammy skin, weak pulse, nausea — move to cool place immediately, apply wet cloth, give ORS, call 104. Heatstroke — medical emergency: temperature above 40 degrees, confusion or altered consciousness, hot dry skin (sweating may stop), rapid strong pulse — Call 108 immediately. While waiting: cool the person rapidly by any means available — pour water, fan, ice packs to neck, armpits, and groin. Do NOT give fluids to someone who is confused. Prevention: Drink water every 30 minutes even when not thirsty. ORS sachets are superior to plain water for anyone doing outdoor work. Never leave any person or animal in a parked vehicle — interior temperature reaches 70 degrees in 20 minutes.',2,20,1,NOW(),NOW()),

-- Course 17: Landslide Risk & Safety
(17,'Landslide Hazards Across India','India records 500-1,000 landslide deaths annually with significant under-reporting in remote Himalayan and Northeast regions. The Geological Survey of India has mapped 0.42 million square kilometres as landslide-prone — approximately 12.6% of India total land area. High-risk states: Uttarakhand, Himachal Pradesh, Jammu and Kashmir, all Northeast states especially Manipur and Mizoram, Kerala (Western Ghats), and Maharashtra (Sahyadri range). Primary triggers: intense monsoon rainfall exceeding 150mm per day, deforestation for agriculture and road construction, unregulated slope cutting for hill roads, and earthquake shaking in mountain terrain. The July 2024 Wayanad landslides in Kerala killed 231 people and displaced 10,000 in a single night, triggered by 572mm of rainfall in 48 hours on slopes denuded for tea plantations.',1,25,1,NOW(),NOW()),
(17,'Landslide Warning Signs and Safe Evacuation','Community warning signs to watch during heavy rainfall: New cracks appearing in ground, roads, or house walls especially diagonal cracks at corners. Tilting or newly leaning trees, fence posts, or utility poles. Doors and windows that suddenly stick or no longer close properly — indicates ground movement. Unusual sounds: rumbling, cracking of trees, or rushing water sounds. Streams suddenly becoming very muddy or turbid. Sudden decrease in stream flow (debris dam forming upstream — very dangerous, sudden outburst flooding follows). Safe evacuation: Move immediately to higher ground or perpendicular to slope — never run downhill along the slide path. If caught in slide: curl into tight ball, protect head with arms. After landslide: secondary slides very common for 24 hours. Stay away. Report to 112.',2,20,1,NOW(),NOW());

